Final Report for Intro to Data Science

Team Members

  • Madison Yonash

Introduction

I use a daily journaling app called Daylio to track my mood and activities that I have done throughout the day. In 2019, I made the accomplishment of tracking this every single day of the year (with some days having multiple entries). Ive always been interested in the data and visualizations that the app has to offer, from creating a color scale of my mood for a particular month to a weekly recap of what happened. However, not all of my questions could be answered by the app itself. I saw that I could download the data as a .csv file, and from there, my exploration of the data began.

The app itself is relatively straightforward: you click one of the moods you create (mine included names like meh, not good but feel like it should be, etc) (which are inherently factors, even if the app doesnt make it seem like it at first glance!), select activities/traits that apply to your day, and write notes if you would like. For the sake of this report, I omitted the notes I had and created a mood_scale (that is a numerical representation of the factors (for ex, multiple moods had the equivalent of a 4/5 so I took this step for my own usability purposes). before uploading the csv file to GitHub.

As a female in her 20s, it is no surprise that I am familiar with astrology. You may have heard the term that X is happening because Mercury is in Retrograde. While Im by no means an expert on astrological occurrences, I thought it would be fun to do some additional exploration to see if this had any correlation with my mood. I also want to use other data sets with factors that may affect my mood. I found a super cool GitHub Repo that relates to this topic.

Tidying Up the Data

Since the data initially came from all years that I have used the app, it is important to make the data tidy and easier to work with.

Load necessary packages:

library(tidyverse) 
library(lubridate) #date and time

Working with the Dailyo Data

Import data, which can be found here:

clean_report <- read_csv("C:/Users/madis/Documents/intro to ds/final_project/DS_Final_Project/data/clean_report.csv")
Rows: 820 Columns: 4
-- Column specification --------------------------------------------------------------------
Delimiter: ","
chr  (2): mood, activities
dbl  (1): mood_scale
date (1): date

i Use `spec()` to retrieve the full column specification for this data.
i Specify the column types or set `show_col_types = FALSE` to quiet this message.

To analyze the data from 2019, we must filter the dataset for entries taken during that year. The use of the lubridate package makes this easy:

report_2019 <- clean_report %>% 
  filter(between(date, as.Date("2019-01-01"), as.Date("2019-12-31")))

If you take a glance at the activities column, you may notice that the observations have a varying number of activities. Here is a sample of some of the observations:

report_2019 %>% 
  select(activities) %>% 
  sample_n(5)

To make it easier to work with this data, we can separate the activities so that each activity is contained within its own observation:

report_2019_sep <- report_2019 %>% 
  separate_rows(activities, sep = "\\|") 

report_2019_sep$activities <- trimws(report_2019_sep$activities, which = c("both"))

Additionally, we can create an additional column that summarizes the average the mood per day. This will let us compare the rating of any particular day in 2019 with other factors.

report_2019_day <- report_2019 %>% 
  group_by(date) %>% 
  summarize(ave_mood = mean(mood_scale, na.rm=T))

Data Description

Now that the data is prepared, lets see what it shows us.

Dailyo Data

In the Tidying Up the Data section, we created a few dataframes from our initial download from the Dailyo app called clean_report.

The one we can most relevantly go back to is the report_2019, which contains all entries for the year 2019 (which is the focus of this report).

The features of the original 2019 dataset include:

  • date | date format (yyyy/mm/dd)
  • mood | character
  • activities | character
  • mood scale | number

Lets see what a few of my days looked like:

report_2019 %>% 
  sample_n(10)

From there, for my own usability purposes, I created two additional dataframes from this report of all 2019 entries. These are report_2019_sep and report_2019_day

In the report_2019_sep data, we have a version of the original dataset, with each observation holding a separate activity category. This was important to do because, as seen earlier, some observations had multiple activities while some had none at all.

#print sample of this report
report_2019_sep %>% 
  sample_n(5)

This will be helpful when looking at possible correlation related to the activities I have done during different days.

In the report_2019_sep data, we have a simpler dataframe. This only includes the date of the observation and the average mood for that particular day. There are 365 observations of this dataset for the 365 days in the year. Lets take a look at it:

#print sample of this report
report_2019_day %>% 
  sample_n(5)

This dataframe will be helpful in completing analysis related to the year as a whole. From here, we can look at trends in average daily mood, compare things on a day by day basis (which would be more difficult with some days having multiple entries or differing numbers of activities).

Mercury in Retrograde Data

The Mercury in Retrograde data comes from this Github Repo.

Per the Repo: The present dataset consists of two features those being:

  • DATE | date format (yyyy/mm/dd)
  • isRetrograde | boolean (0 or 1) isRetrograde has a value of 1 (one) when mercury was in retrograde during the respective date and 0 (zero) when it was following a normal course.

The original GitHub Repo also provided a photo of a graphical representation of one of the years (2018) of the data:

Before beginning our analysis, lets print a summary of the report_2019 dataset:

summary(report_2019)

This shows that, despite our 365 days in a year, we have 393 observations. It is also interesting to note the mean of the mood scale: from here, we see that in 2019 it was a 3.743/5. Not a bad number! Note that this is averaging all 393 entries and is not finding the mean based on a daily average.

Univariate Data Analysis

This section focuses on looking into the mood scale and activities of the reports individually.

Mood

First, lets see how my feelings stacked up by visualizing the distribution of individual entries of my moods.

report_2019 %>% 
  ggplot() +
  geom_bar(mapping = aes(mood_scale)) +
  labs(title = "Distribution of Moods", x = "Mood", y = "Count") +
  theme_minimal()

We can also compare this to the distribution of the daily average:

report_2019_day %>% 
  ggplot() +
  geom_bar(mapping = aes(ave_mood)) +
  labs(title = "Distribution of Daily Moods", x = "Mood", y = "Count") +
  theme_minimal()

Note that, upon finding the distribution of the daily average, most entries were an integer, however some days had scores that fell between the ranges (ie: there was an entry that was 4/5 in the morning and one that was 3/5 in the evening, therefore the daily mood was 3.5). The number of these is significantly less than the integer entries, however. There are also no entries that had the mood of 4.5.

report_2019_day %>% 
  summarize(avg_daily_mood = mean(ave_mood))

The average daily mood is also slightly higher than the average mood of all entries.

Activities

Next, lets see what kinds of things I did over the year.

#find how frequently i did different things
report_2019_sep %>%
  group_by(activities) %>% 
  summarize(count = n()) %>% 
  arrange(desc(count))

Its a bit sad that my most frequent activity was doing homework

Moving on, lets create a visualization of the frequency I completed different activities:

report_2019_sep %>%
  ggplot() +
  geom_bar(mapping = aes(fct_rev(fct_infreq(activities)), 
                         fill = activities)) +
  coord_flip() +
  theme_minimal() +
  guides(fill="none") +
  labs(title = "Distribution of Activities", x = "Activity", y = "Count")

Multivariate Data Analysis

Changes over the Year

First, lets try and graph my average daily mood over the course of the year.

report_2019_day %>% 
  ggplot() +
  geom_line(mapping = aes(x = date, y = ave_mood)) +
  labs(title = "Change in Daily Mood Throughout the Year", y = "Daily Average Mood",
       x = "Date")

Wow, thats turbulent! This isnt super insightful, so further breaking down the data may help us learn more about it.

Montly Averages

Lets see how my mood during the different months in the year compare.

# before we go into looking at the months, create a new dataframe that is easier to work with
# make additional columns for month and day
report_2019_months <- report_2019_day %>% 
  mutate(day = format(report_2019_day$date, "%d")) %>% 
  mutate(month = month(ymd(date), label = T)) %>% 
  select(ave_mood, month, day)
report_2019_months$day <- as.numeric(report_2019_months$day)
# find average mood by month as well as variation
report_2019_months %>% 
  group_by(month) %>%
  summarize(avg_montly_mood = mean(ave_mood), variation = var(ave_mood))

Here we can see the average mood for the month as a whole, as well as the variation for each month.

To visualize this:

report_2019_months %>% 
  group_by(month) %>%
  summarize(avg_montly_mood = mean(ave_mood), variation = var(ave_mood)) %>% 
  ggplot() +
  geom_point(aes(
    x = month,
    y = avg_montly_mood,
    size = 3, 
    color = month)) +
  ylim(1,5) +
    labs(title = "Average Mood by Month",
         y = "Mood Rating",
         x = "Month") +
  guides(size="none", color = "none") +
  theme_minimal()

This gives us an idea of how I was doing, by the mean mood, month to month. It was relatively consistent, with the end of the year being slightly lower. A possible explanation for this was the start of senior year of high school, complete with everything from college applications to International Baccalaureate exams!

Mood Over Each Month

This, however, does not show us how I was doing within the month itself. Another visualization that we can create could be to show how my mood changed from month to month, comparing the actual changes within the month rather than the mean for the month as a whole.

#visualize data
report_2019_months %>%
  ggplot( aes(x=day, y=ave_mood, group=month, color=month)) +
    geom_line() +
  ggtitle("Average Mood by Month") +
  labs(x = "Day", y ="Average Daily Mood") +
  theme_minimal()

Thats pretty ugly. Since there are so many lines on one chart, it is difficult to compare the trends within each month. Lets try again:

# try again
tmp <- report_2019_months %>% 
  mutate(month2 = month)

tmp %>%
  ggplot( aes(x=day, y=ave_mood)) +
    geom_line( data=tmp %>% dplyr::select(-month), aes(group=month2), color="grey", size=0.5, alpha=0.5) +
    geom_line( aes(color=month), color="#5e08a8", size=1.2 )+
    labs(title = "How Each Month's Daily Mood Compares",
         x = "Day", 
         y ="Average Daily Mood") +
    facet_wrap(~month)

I think thats pretty neat! Here, we can see how the average daily mood changed throughout the course of each of the months. Some months were a little more varied than others.

Mood and Activities

To see how the average daily mood was affected by individual activities, the report_2019_sep can be joined with the report_2019_day dataframe.

# join average mood to report_2019_sep
report_2019_activities <- left_join(report_2019_sep, report_2019_day, by = "date")

How does the overall mood of the day compare to the activities done? To investigate this, we can find the mean mood for all days an activity is done.

report_2019_activities %>% 
  group_by(activities) %>% 
  summarize(avg = mean(mood_scale)) %>% 
  arrange(desc(avg))

For context, I used to go to Wawa to hang out with my friends for hours and get food/drinks while we were there. Quality time indicates that I spent time with my boyfriend

Lets see the 5 highest and lowest mood by activities:

head(report_2019_activities %>% 
  group_by(activities) %>% 
  summarize(avg = mean(mood_scale)) %>% 
  arrange(desc(avg)))
tail(report_2019_activities %>% 
  group_by(activities) %>% 
  summarize(avg = mean(mood_scale)) %>% 
  arrange(desc(avg)))

Overall, it makes sense that activities that relate to hanging out with friends and loved ones correlated with a higher average mood, while things like sick and babysitting ranked lower.

Lets see this in a visualization!

report_2019_activities %>% 
  group_by(activities) %>% 
  summarize(avg = mean(mood_scale)) %>% 
  ggplot() +
  geom_col(aes(x = fct_reorder(activities, avg),
               y = avg,
               fill = activities)) +
  theme_minimal() +
  labs(title = "Average Daily Mood on Days where an Activity Was Done",
       x = "Activity",
       y = "Average Mood") +
  guides(fill="none") +
  coord_flip()

Another visualization that we can do that relates to this aspect of the investigation is the distribution of mood for each activity. Lets make it:

# make mood scale temporarily a character
temp <- report_2019_activities %>% 
  mutate(mood_scale = as.character(report_2019_activities$mood_scale))

# create visualization
temp %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = fct_rev(fct_infreq(activities)), 
             fill = mood_scale)) +
  geom_bar(position = "stack") +
  labs(y = "Proportion",
       x = "Activities",
       title = "Proportion of Daily Mood by Activity",
       fill = "Daily Mood") +
  coord_flip()

This provides some additional insight to the previous visualization of the average daily mood. For example, Wawa has the highest average daily mood associated with it, but there are significantly less observations of this activity than there are relax, for example.

Data Analysis

Now that we have completed some exploratory data analysis, we can answer some questions about the data.

How was my mood during mercury retrograde?

This is the fun one that weve been waiting for. First, I will join the mercury dataset to the report_2019_day set.

# join the mercury dataset to the report_2019_day set
retrograde_mood <- left_join(report_2019_day, mercury_in_retrograde, by = c("date" = "DATE"))
retrograde_mood <- left_join(retrograde_mood, report_2019, by =  "date")

Find the mean mood for when isRetrograde is TRUE.

#find normal mood and variation of all entries
retrograde_mood %>% 
    summarize(avg_mood = mean(ave_mood), variation = var(ave_mood))

#find mood and variation of all entries when isRetrograde is TRUE
retrograde_mood %>% 
  filter(isRetrograde == T) %>% 
  summarize(avg_mood_r = mean(ave_mood), variation_mood_r = var(ave_mood))

As we see, the mean mood is slightly lower (3.63) when mercury is in retrograde. Additionally, my mood variation was higher (.94) when mercury was in retrograde. Considering one of the features of mercury retrograde you hear about most is that it makes you feel all over the place, this seems to makes sense!

The question that naturally comes up next is, what happened during those weeks? Lets find out:

retrograde_mood %>% 
  filter(isRetrograde == T)

We can also visualize each of these retrogrades:

#trying to visualize it
retrograde_mood %>% 
  mutate(week = 0)

retrograde_mood$week <- ifelse(retrograde_mood$date == between(date, as.Date("2019-03-07"), as.Date("2019-03-29")),
1, 
retrograde_mood$week)

Does the school year affect the activities performed?

Earlier, we found that homework was the most frequent activity. Lets see if we can find the approximate time that summer is based on this.

report_2019_activities %>% 
  filter(activities == c("homework", "test")) %>%
